<br>
The original question of this thread, &quot;Are there any forms of Terrorism that are good?&quot; begs two different questions in response- what deos the word &quot;terrorism&quot; mean, and what does the word &quot;good&quot; mean.  <br>
Here is the only dictionary definition of terrorism yet seen on this thread:<br>
<br>
&quot;The unlawful use or threatened use of force or violence by a person or an organized group against people or property with the intention of intimidating or coercing societies or governments, often for ideological or political reasons.&quot;<br>
<br>
Now, since war has been &quot;unlawful&quot; since at the very latest, 1921 (Kellogg-Briand Pact), I think War fits rather nicely here, even though as a matter of both fact and law, every nation considers the right to make war a basic part of sovereignity.<br>
<br>
A final question, the American Civil War cost the lives of nearly 1,000,000 Americans to end slavery and put to rest the question of states Rights.  I fail to see how it would somehow have been worse to blow up some public building, kill a few thousand &quot;civilians&quot; and accomplish the same purpose.  I'm not saying it could have been done- see Northern Ireland for an example of Terrorism as an excercise in futility- but would that have been more atrocious than a million dead? I don't see it.<br>
<br>
Thanks,<br>
