itera <p><IMG SRC="http://user.tninet.se/~mhf993y/anna/sig2.jpg"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/ukeldal.showPublicProfile?language=EN>keldal</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Board Veteran</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(1/11/02 9:53:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=808.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: are there any forms of terrorism that are good?</span><hr size=1> The question, IMO, is who you are attacking.  If you are attacking a supporter of an enemy regime or the regime itself then you may have legitimate targets.  Slamming a plane load of civilians into a civilian office building is not an act of war, it is an act designed to inspire terror in the population of a country.<br>
<br>
The bombing of Japan in WWII occurred under the assumption, probably correct based on our experience fighting the Japanese in the pacific, that the US was at war with the entire population of Japan and that the enemy would not surrender even if they were obviously beaten in normal combat.  To end that war it was decided that it would ultimately cost less lives to demonstrate total military supremacy to the enemy by destroying two cities.  I don't know if I would have made the same choice, but in retrospect is seems to be the correct one.<br>
<br>
Treistaania you are wrong, I think, about the French resistance.  They used guerrilla tactics not terrorist tactics.  They weren't planting bombs on the street to kill random folks walking around to protest the Nazi occupation.  They instead did everything they could to kill Nazis.<br>
<br>
Perhaps it makes more sense to say that war has achievable goals but terrorism does not.  In a revolution your goal is to replace your existing government with one more to your liking.  To achieve that you attack the structures and organizations that allow the current government to function.  A terrorist that has a problem with that same government ultimately seems to dislike an idea.  Since you can't fight an idea you lash out at the things that represent that idea to you.  If you hate western culture you might fixate on the US as the most successful western country and begin shooting at anything that symbolizes the US.  Ultimately you can't effect a change in your situation because your enemy isn't physical and can't be fought.<br>
<br>
--Keldal<br>
