<br>
Wearing a uniform makes you an acceptable victim of violence.  Its as simple as that.  When you join the military you take on all of your governments enemies and become a target for them.  You accept that at any given moment your life may be violently taken from you.  This is especially true for most modern militaries where all enlisted personnel have joined voluntarily.<br>
<br>
Since the Pact of Paris (the Kellogg-Briand Pact) wasnt signed until 1928 it has no bearing on the Civil War aspects of this conversation.  Truthfully, seeing as how worthless the Pact was (and is) I dont really see that it holds much bearing period except in the textbooks as a failed half-attempt at peace.<br>
<br>
&quot;A final question, the American Civil War cost the lives of nearly 1,000,000 Americans to end slavery and put to rest the question of states Rights. I fail to see how it would somehow have been worse to blow up some public building, kill a few thousand &quot;civilians&quot; and accomplish the same purpose. I'm not saying it could have been done...but would that have been more atrocious than a million dead? I don't see it.&quot;<br>
<br>
It would have been worse because the targets would have been civilian populations.  A huge majority of the americans who died in the civil war were military personnel.  The armies of both the North and the South (with the exception of some black slaves who were pressed into fighting for the South) were completely voluntary.  By joining the armies of their respective sides, those who died in the civil war accepted the fact that their death was acceptable to gain the goals of their side.<br>
