<br>
Virtually every civilian in a country contributes to the capacity of their country to continue aggression to one degree or another.  Unless... they have somehow managed to miraculousy find a way to extricate themselves from their nation's economy.  Countries can't go on the aggressive without an economy.  They can try but they won't last for long.  It's impossible to maintain production and effort when your cities are rioting.  Everytime they spend a dollar, a peso, or whatever they contribute to their nation's economy and ability to pay to financially maintain a war effort.  Even those people on the plane had jobs and were working and functioning members of the US economy.  War is not going to distinguish you as being a soldier by what time of day it is or wether you may be on vacation.  &quot;Whelp time to clock out now... phweew... I'm no longer a target until 8am tomorrow.&quot;  I wish it was that clear cut and nice but it's just not going to be.<br>
<br>
Wether they build slurpee machines or manufacture tank barrels they are still participating in the maintaining of our country's economy and it's ability to keep troops on foreign soils and at sea.  Why do you think Bin Laden was going after the world trade center and the stock market?  He was hoping to cripple our monetary ability to keep and maintain the troops in the middle east.  Fortunately, he didn't do his homework and had no clue that our economy wasn't as centralized as he hoped it would be.  He migh have succeeded back in the 1920's as the depression proved how centralized our economy had become around the stock market.  Thankfully, there's enough safe guards in place and alternative investments that we are no longer that centralized.  He made a dent though, I'll give him that much.<br>
<br>
To bring back another WW 2 example... something like 95% or more of the US civilian population at home was actively participating in the war effort.  From metal recycyling to tire scrounging to candy bar making... virtually the entire US work force was directed towards the war effort in both support and maintenance of our troops over seas.  By your definition practically every US civilian was a soldier and a legitimate target at that time.  Even if they had gotten on a plane to go see their mother or father, etc...<br>
<br>
