To the arabians, and Osama Bin Laden, the United States is the supporter of an enemy regime...that which is Israel.<br>
<br>
I am sure that also, to them, this was not an act of terrorism but an act of war.<br>
<br>
The founders of the United States were probably very much terrorists.  Aside from the Boston Tea Party, the colonists in favor of revolution did what they could to rally people under their flag, and cause fear and terror in their enemy, through subterfuge and a lot of propaganda.<br>
<br>
As they say, history is written by those who win wars.  A lot of acts that the US considers horrendous, we've done ourselves at some time or another.  Pearl Harbor and the St. Valentines Massecre (in Vietnam)?  Same thing as George Washington crossing the Deleware.<br>
<br>
Suppose, for a moment, that the United States, through some great miracle, was overthrown by the forces of Osama Bin Laden in a series of bloody battles followed by an invasion.  The resulting future was to become an arabian empire led by him, that eventually prospers as much as the United States ever did.<br>
<br>
200 years from now, would the destruction of the World Trade Center be referred to as an act of terrorism, or an act of heroism that caused the eventual forming of a great and wonderful empire?<br>
<br>
