<br>
The factory is a target.  The neighborhood where the workers live is NOT.<br>
<br>
Ullric, there is a difference between revolutionaries and terrorists, as I mentioned in an earlier post.  The boston tea party was not an act of terrorism, it was an act of vandalism.  It's always struck me as unfortunate that high-school history teachers are stuck with books that claim this is a patriotic act:  a bunch of men, angry about taxes, looted and vandalised the business property of British merchants.  I'm not aware of any organized efforts by the american revolutionaries to shoot torries &amp; burndown their houses.  Tempers may have flaired &amp; someone may have taken advantage of local sentiment to get back at a neighbor, but for the most part the fight was constrained to battlefields.<br>
<br>
History, in the short term, is written by the victors but it's a bit ridiculous tho suggest that the actual attack on the world trade center could ever be considered a heroic act.  At best the facts would be rearranged to justify the action.<br>
<br>
